Based on the results above, the photocatalytic mechanism to degrade the OTC (Fig. 12
                        ) was proposed as follows: firstly, the porous 3D network structure and large specific surface area favored the polyimide aerogels to adsorb small molecules, such as organic pollutant and O2. Secondly, owing to the upconvertion of the CQDs, the visible light absorption ability of polyimide aerogel was improved. The electrons could be more easily motived to CB edges from VB edges under the visible light. The left hole h+ could effectively oxidize the OTC. Meanwhile, the electrons could reduce O2 to ·O2
                        –, which could also degrade the OTC. Thirdly, the CQDs had good conductivity and acted as electron-sinks, which favored charge transport and separation. Fourthly, PI/CQDs could form a heterojunction, which reduced the band gap and made photoexcited electrons effectively migrate from PI aerogel to CQDs via heterojunction interface. Subsequently, the recombination between electron-hole pairs was hindered effectively, which prolonged the lifetime of charge carrier and facilitated their reaction with adsorbed molecules such as O2. Finally, the PI/CQDs aerogels had high photocatalytic property.
